<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:lang="en-US" xml:id="sec-derivative-ww">
  <title>Additional Worked-Out Problems</title>

   <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-intro">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-intro"/> Introduction and Motivation for Derivatives</title>

      <example xml:id="ex-deriv-ww-1">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the average rate of change of the function <m>f(x) = \tan(x)-x</m> on the interval <m>[-\frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{4}]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find the average rate of change of the function <m>f(x) = \tan(x)-x</m> on the interval <m>[-\frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{4}]</m>, 
            we use the formula for the average rate of change:
          </p>
          <me> \text{Average Rate of Change} = \frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a} </me>
          <p>
            where <m>a = -\frac{\pi}{4}</m> and <m>b = \frac{\pi}{4}</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            First, we calculate <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>:
          </p>
          <me> f\left(-\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \tan\left(-\frac{\pi}{4}\right) - \left(-\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = -1 + \frac{\pi}{4} </me>
          <me> f\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) = \tan\left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right) - \frac{\pi}{4} = 1 - \frac{\pi}{4} </me>
          <p>
            Now, we substitute these values into the average rate of change formula and simplify:
          </p>
          <me> 
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            \text{Average Rate of Change} &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{\left(1 - \frac{\pi}{4}\right) - \left(-1 + \frac{\pi}{4}\right)}{\frac{\pi}{4} - \left(-\frac{\pi}{4}\right)} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{1 - \frac{\pi}{4} + 1 - \frac{\pi}{4}}{\frac{\pi}{4} + \frac{\pi}{4}} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2 - \frac{\pi}{2}}{\frac{\pi}{2}} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{2}{\frac{\pi}{2}} - 1 \\
            &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{4}{\pi} - 1
            \end{array}
          </me>
          <p>
            Therefore, the average rate of change of the function <m>f(x) = \tan(x)-x</m> on the interval <m>[-\frac{\pi}{4}, \frac{\pi}{4}]</m> is <m>\frac{4}{\pi} - 1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>


<example xml:id="ex-secant-tangent-polynomial">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x)=x^2 - 4x + 1</m>.
    </p>

<p> 
      (a) 
        Find the slope of the secant line joining 
        <m>P(1,f(1))</m> and <m>Q(5,f(5))</m>.
      </p>

      <p> (b) 
        Find the slope of the secant line joining 
        <m>P(2,f(2))</m> and <m>Q(2+h,f(2+h))</m>.
      </p>
      
       <p> (c) 
        Find the slope of the tangent line at 
        <m>P(2,f(2))</m>.
      </p>
      <p> (d)
        Find the equation of the tangent line at 
        <m>P(2,f(2))</m>.
      </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>(a) The slope of the secant line is</p>

    <me>
      \frac{f(5)-f(1)}{5-1}.
    </me>

    <p>Compute the function values:</p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f(1) &amp; =&amp; 1 - 4 + 1 = -2, \\
      f(5) &amp; =&amp; 25 - 20 + 1 = 6.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <me>
      \frac{6-(-2)}{4} = \frac{8}{4} = 2.
    </me>

    <p>
      So the slope of the secant line is <m>2</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(b) The slope of the secant line is</p>

    <me>
      \frac{f(2+h)-f(2)}{h}.
    </me>

    <p>First compute:</p>

    <me>
      f(2) = 4 - 8 + 1 = -3.
    </me>

    <me>
      f(2+h) = (2+h)^2 - 4(2+h) + 1.
    </me>

    <p>Expand:</p>

    <me>
      f(2+h) = 4 + 4h + h^2 - 8 - 4h + 1 = h^2 - 3.
    </me>

    <p>So the difference quotient becomes</p>

    <me>
      \frac{(h^2 - 3) - (-3)}{h}
      =
      \frac{h^2}{h}
      =
      h.
    </me>

    <p>(c) The slope of the tangent line is the limit as <m>h \to 0</m>:</p>

    <me>
      \lim_{h\to 0} h = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      So the slope of the tangent line at <m>x=2</m> is <m>0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(d) Using point-slope form:</p>

    <me>
      y - (-3) = 0(x-2).
    </me>

    <me>
      y = -3.
    </me>

    <p>
      The tangent line is horizontal at <m>y=-3</m>.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>



    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-defn">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-defn"/> Definition of the Derivative</title>

<example xml:id="ex-derivative-limit-def-cubic">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>f(x)=x^3-2x</m> near <m>x=1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) 
        Simplify the difference quotient as much as possible:
        <me>
          \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p> (b)
        Use your result from part (a) and the limit definition of the derivative to calculate <m>f'(1)</m>:
        <me>
          f'(1)=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}.
        </me>
      </p>

      <p> (c)
        Consider the following table of values of <m>f(x)</m> near <m>x=1</m>.
        Use difference quotients to approximate <m>f'(1)</m>.
      </p> 
<me>
\begin{array}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
x &amp; 1 &amp; 1.1 &amp; 1.01 &amp; 1.001 &amp; 0.99 \\
\hline
f(x) &amp; -1.000 &amp; -0.869 &amp; -0.989699 &amp; -0.998997 &amp; -1.009701 \\
\hline
\end{array}
</me>
        
        <p>
          Approximate <m>f'(1)</m> by computing the following difference quotients:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            For <m>h=0.1</m>, compute
            <m>\dfrac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>h=0.01</m>, compute
            <m>\dfrac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>h=0.001</m>, compute
            <m>\dfrac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            For <m>h=-0.01</m>, compute
            <m>\dfrac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>


  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p><em>(a)</em> First compute:</p>

    <me>
      f(1+h)=(1+h)^3-2(1+h).
    </me>

    <p>
      Expand:
    </p>

    <me>
      (1+h)^3 = 1+3h+3h^2+h^3.
    </me>

    <me>
      f(1+h)
      =
      1+3h+3h^2+h^3-2-2h
      =
      -1+h+3h^2+h^3.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since <m>f(1)=1^3-2(1)=-1</m>, we have:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}
      =
      \frac{(-1+h+3h^2+h^3)-(-1)}{h}.
    </me>

    <me>
      =
      \frac{h+3h^2+h^3}{h}
      =
      1+3h+h^2.
    </me>

    <p><em>(b)</em> Now take the limit:</p>

    <me>
      f'(1)
      =
      \lim_{h\to 0}(1+3h+h^2)
      =
      1.
    </me>

    <p><em>(c)</em> Using the table:</p>

    <p>
      For <m>h=0.1</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{-0.869-(-1)}{0.1}
      =
      \frac{0.131}{0.1} = 0.131 \cdot 10
      =
      1.31.
    </me>

    <p>
      For <m>h=0.01</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{-0.989699-(-1)}{0.01}
      =
      \frac{0.010301}{0.01} = 0.010301 \cdot 100
      =
      1.0301.
    </me>

    <p>
      For <m>h=0.001</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{-0.998997-(-1)}{0.001}
      =
      \frac{0.001003}{0.001} = 0.001003 \cdot 1000
      =
      1.003.
    </me>

    <p>
      For <m>h=-0.01</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{-1.009701-(-1)}{-0.01}
      =
      \frac{-0.009701}{-0.01} = -0.009701 \cdot -100
      =
      0.9701.
    </me>

    <p>
      These values approach <m>1</m>, confirming that
      <m>f'(1)=1</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
      
<example xml:id="ex-velocity-from-graph-bounce">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>y=p(t)</m> be the height (in meters) of a rubber ball dropped from a ledge at time <m>t=0</m> seconds.
      The ball hits the ground at <m>t=0.9</m> seconds and then immediately bounces upward with a smaller velocity.
      A graph of <m>p(t)</m> is shown below.
    </p>


  <image source="images/ballBouncing.png" width="85%">
    <shortdescription>
      A graph of height versus time. The curve begins at time 0 with height 12 meters and decreases smoothly,
      curving downward as time increases. The graph reaches height 0 at time 0.9 seconds.
      At that point there is a sharp corner. After 0.9 seconds, the graph changes direction
      and increases along a straight line segment, representing the ball rising upward
      at a constant but smaller speed than it had while falling.
    </shortdescription>
  </image>

    <p>
      (a) What are the units of <m>p'(t)</m>? Explain what the sign of <m>p'(t)</m> tells you about the motion of the ball.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Use the graph to approximate <m>p'(t)</m> for <m>0.8 &lt; t &lt; 0.9</m>. What is the velocity of the ball just before it hits the ground?
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) Use the graph to approximate the velocity of the ball immediately after the bounce (for <m>0.9 &lt; t &lt; 1.0</m>)?
    </p>

    <p>
      (d) Compare the left-hand and right-hand derivatives at <m>t=0.9</m>. Does <m>p'(0.9)</m> exist? Explain your reasoning using the graph.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) Height is measured in meters and time in seconds, so <m>p'(t)</m> has units of meters per second (m/sec).
      If <m>p'(t)</m> is negative, the ball is moving downward.
      If <m>p'(t)</m> is positive, the ball is moving upward.
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) For <m>0.8 &lt; t &lt; 0.9</m>,
      we have <m>p(0.8) \approx 2.5</m> and <m>p(0.9) = 0</m>.
      Just before impact, the average velocity is approximately
    </p> 
    <me>
      \frac{p(0.9)-p(0.8)}{0.9-0.8}
      =
      \frac{0-2.5}{0.1}
      =
      -25.
    </me>
    <p> 
      So the ball is moving downward at approximately <m>25</m> m/sec just before hitting the ground.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) For <m>0.9 &lt; t &lt; 1.0</m>,
      we have <m>p(0.9) = 0</m> and <m>p(1.0) \approx 1</m>. Therefore the average velocity is approximately
    </p> 
    <me>
      \frac{p(1.0)-p(0.9)}{1.0-0.9}
      =
      \frac{1-0}{0.1}
      =
      10.
    </me>
    <p> 
      So immediately after the bounce, the ball is moving upward at approximately <m>10</m> m/sec.
    </p>

    <p>
      (d) The left-hand derivative at <m>t=0.9</m> is approximately <m>-25</m>,
      while the right-hand derivative is <m>10</m>.
      Since these values are not equal, the derivative does not exist at <m>t=0.9</m>.
      Graphically, the function has a sharp corner at the bounce point.
    </p>

  </solution>
</example>




<example xml:id="ex-difference-quotient-rational-position">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>p(t)=\dfrac{2t-1}{5+t}</m> be the position of an object at time <m>t</m>.
      Here <m>p</m> is measured in meters and <m>t</m> is measured in seconds.
    </p>

        <p>
          (a) Simplify the following difference quotient as much as possible:
        </p>
        <me>
          \frac{p(t+h)-p(t)}{h}.
        </me>
     

        <p>
          (b) Use your result from part (a) and the limit definition of the derivative to
          calculate the instantaneous velocity of the object at time <m>t</m>.
        </p>
        <me>
          v(t)=p'(t)=\lim_{h\to 0}\frac{p(t+h)-p(t)}{h}.
        </me>


        <p>
          (c) What is the object's velocity at <m>t=1</m> second?
        </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
        <p> (a) 
          First compute
        </p>
        <me>
          p(t+h)=\frac{2(t+h)-1}{5+t+h}
          =
          \frac{2t+2h-1}{5+t+h}.
        </me>

        <p>
          So the difference quotient becomes
        </p>
        <me>
          \frac{ \frac{2t+2h-1}{5+t+h} - \frac{2t-1}{5+t} }{h}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Combine the fractions over a common denominator:
        </p>
        <me>
          =
          \frac{
            (2t+2h-1)(5+t) - (2t-1)(5+t+h)
          }{
            h(5+t+h)(5+t)
          }.
        </me>

        <p>
          After expanding and simplifying, this reduces to
        </p>
        <me>
          \frac{11}{(5+t+h)(5+t)}.
        </me>

        <p> (b)
          Now take the limit as <m>h\to 0</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          v(t)=\lim_{h\to 0}
          \frac{11}{(5+t+h)(5+t)}
          =
          \frac{11}{(5+t)^2}.
        </me>

        <p> (c) 
          Evaluate at <m>t=1</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          v(1)=\frac{11}{(6)^2}=\frac{11}{36}.
        </me>
        <p>
          So the velocity at <m>t=1</m> second is <m>\dfrac{11}{36}</m> m/s.
        </p>
  </solution>
</example>





    </subsection>


    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-rules">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-rules"/> Basic Differentiation Rules</title>

      
<example xml:id="ex-derivatives-multi">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = 2+3x^2 - 5x + \dfrac{8}{x^3}</m>. Evaluate the following:
    </p>

    <p>(a) <m>f'(x) =</m> </p>
    <p>(b) <m>f'(2) =</m> </p>
    <p>(c) <m>f''(x) =</m> </p>
    <p>(d) <m>f''(2) =</m> </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p> (a) To find <m>f'(x)</m>, we differentiate each term of the function. </p> 
    <p>Recall that <m>\dfrac{8}{x^3} = 8x^{-3}</m>, so we can apply the power rule to this term as well.</p> 
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f'(x) &amp; =&amp; 0 + 6x - 5 - 24x^{-4} \\
      &amp; =&amp; 6x - 5 - \frac{24}{x^4}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p> (b) To find <m>f'(2)</m>, we substitute <m>x=2</m> into the expression for <m>f'(x)</m>: </p>
    <me>
      f'(2) = 6(2) - 5 - \frac{24}{(2)^4} = 12 - 5 - \frac{24}{16} = 7 - \frac{3}{2} = \frac{11}{2}.
    </me>
    <p> (c) To find <m>f''(x)</m>, we differentiate <m>f'(x)</m>: </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f''(x) &amp; =&amp; 6 + 0 + 96x^{-5} \\
      &amp; =&amp; 6 + \frac{96}{x^5}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p> (d) To find <m>f''(2)</m>, we substitute <m>x=2</m> into the expression for <m>f''(x)</m>: </p>
    <me>
      f''(2) = 6 + \frac{96}{(2)^5} = 6 + \frac{96}{32} = 6 + 3 = 9.
    </me>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-derivative-ww-2">
<statement>
    <p> Let <m> f(x) = \dfrac{3x^2 - 5x + 4}{x^3 + 1}</m>. </p>
    <p> (a)  Find <m>f'(1)</m>. </p>
    <p> (b)  Find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>. </p>
    <p> (c) Find the equation of the perpendicular line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>. </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) To find <m>f'(1)</m>, we first need to find the derivative <m>f'(x)</m> using the quotient rule. 
      The quotient rule states that if <m>f(x) = \dfrac{g(x)}{h(x)}</m>, then
      <me>
        f'(x) = \frac{g'(x)h(x) - g(x)h'(x)}{(h(x))^2}.
      </me>
      In our case, let <m>g(x) = 3x^2 - 5x + 4</m> and <m>h(x) = x^3 + 1</m>. 
      We compute:
      <me>
        g'(x) = 6x - 5, \quad h'(x) = 3x^2.
      </me>
      Now we can apply the quotient rule:
      <me>
        f'(x) = \frac{(6x - 5)(x^3 + 1) - (3x^2 - 5x + 4)(3x^2)}{(x^3 + 1)^2}.
      </me>
      <p>Now we substitute <m>x=1</m> into the expression for <m>f'(x)</m> to find <m>f'(1)</m>: </p>
      <me>
        f'(1) = \frac{(6 - 5)(2) - (3 - 5 + 4)(3)}{(2)^2}
        = \frac{2 - 6}{4}
        = \frac{-4}{4}
        = -1.
        </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      (b) To find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>, we first need to find the coordinates of the point on the graph at <m>x=1</m>. 
      We compute:
      <me>
        f(1) = \frac{3(1)^2 - 5(1) + 4}{(1)^3 + 1} = \frac{3 - 5 + 4}{2} = \frac{2}{2} = 1.
      </me>
      So the point of tangency is <m>(1, 1)</m>. 
      The slope of the tangent line is given by <m>f'(1) = -1</m>. 
      Using the point-slope form of a line, we can write the equation of the tangent line as:
      <me>
        y - 1 = -1(x - 1).
      </me>
      Simplifying this gives:
      <me>
        y = -x + 2.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) To find the equation of the perpendicular line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>, we first need to find the slope of the perpendicular line. 
      The slope of the tangent line is <m>-1</m>, so the <alert>slope of the perpendicular line is the negative reciprocal</alert> of <m>-1</m>, which is <m>1</m>. 
      Using the point-slope form of a line again, we can write the equation of the perpendicular line as:
      <me>
        y - 1 = 1(x - 1).
      </me>
      Simplifying this gives:
      <me>
        y = x.
      </me>
    </p>
  </solution>
  </example>

<example xml:id="ex-deriv-values-at-point">
  <title>Using Given Function and Derivative Values</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are differentiable functions and that
    </p>

    <me>
      f(1) = -2, 
      \quad f'(1) = 4, 
      \quad g(1) = 5, 
      \quad g'(1) = -3.
    </me>

    <p>
      Evaluate the following derivatives at <m>x=1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>(a) <m>\displaystyle \left.\frac{d}{dx}(3f - 2g)\right|_{x=1}</m></p>

    <p>(b) <m>\displaystyle \left.\frac{d}{dx}(fg)\right|_{x=1}</m></p>

    <p>(c) <m>\displaystyle \left.\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)\right|_{x=1}</m></p>

    <p>(d) <m>\displaystyle \left.\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(\frac{g}{f}\right)\right|_{x=1}</m></p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) We use the linearity of differentiation:
    </p>

    <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
      \left.\frac{d}{dx}(3f - 2g)\right|_{x=1} &amp; = &amp; 3f'(1) - 2g'(1) \\
      &amp; = &amp; 3(4) - 2(-3) = 12 + 6 = 18.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      (b) We use the product rule:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \left.\frac{d}{dx}(fg)\right|_{x=1} &amp; = &amp; f'(1)g(1) + f(1)g'(1) \\
      &amp; = &amp; (4)(5) + (-2)(-3) = 20 + 6 = 26.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      (c) We use the quotient rule:
    </p>

    <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
      \left.\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(\frac{f}{g}\right)\right|_{x=1} &amp; = &amp; \frac{f'(1)g(1) - f(1)g'(1)}{(g(1))^2} \\
      &amp; = &amp; \frac{(4)(5) - (-2)(-3)}{5^2} \\
      &amp; = &amp; \frac{20 - 6}{25} = \frac{14}{25}.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      (d) Again, we use the quotient rule:
    </p>

    <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
      \left.\frac{d}{dx}\!\left(\frac{g}{f}\right)\right|_{x=1} &amp; = &amp; \frac{g'(1)f(1) - g(1)f'(1)}{(f(1))^2} \\
      &amp; = &amp; \frac{-3(-2) - 5(4)}{(-2)^2} \\
      &amp; = &amp; \frac{6 - 20}{4} = \frac{-14}{4} = -\frac{7}{2}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-horizontal-tangents-poly">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find all points of the graph of <m>f(x)=x^3-6x^2+1</m> that have horizontal tangents.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Horizontal tangents occur where the slope (derivative) is zero. So we are looking to solve the equation <m>f'(x)=0</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f(x) &amp; = &amp; x^3-6x^2+1 \\
      f'(x) &amp; = &amp; 3x^2-12x \\
            &amp; = &amp; 3(x^2-4x) \\
            &amp; = &amp; 3x(x-4).
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Set <m>f'(x)=0 \implies</m>
      <m>3x(x-4)=0</m>, so <m>x=0</m> or <m>x=4</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore, the horizontal tangents occur at <m>x=0</m> and <m>x=4</m>. To find the corresponding points on the graph, we compute:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f(0) &amp; = &amp; 1, \\
      f(4) &amp; = &amp; 64 - 96 + 1 = -31.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      Thus, the points of the graph that have horizontal tangents are <m>(0, 1)</m> and <m>(4, -31)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-derivative-triple-product">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the derivative of the given function.
    </p>

    <me>
      y = x(x^2+5)\sqrt{x+1}.
    </me>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p> 
    There are multiple ways to approach this problem. One way is to first simplify the expression for <m>y</m> and then differentiate. 
    Another way is to apply the product rule multiple times without simplifying first. Here, we will take the simpler route and simplify first.
    </p> 
    <p>
      First, we can rewrite <m>y</m> as:
    </p>
    <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
      y &amp; = &amp; x(x^2+5)(x+1)^{1/2} \\
        &amp; = &amp; (x^3 + 5x)(x+1)^{1/2}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      Now we can apply the product rule to differentiate <m>y</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \dfrac{dy}{dx} &amp; = &amp; \left[(x^3 + 5x)(x+1)^{1/2}\right]' \\
                     &amp; = &amp; (3x^2 + 5)(x+1)^{1/2} + (x^3 + 5x)\cdot\frac{1}{2}(x+1)^{-1/2} \\
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p> Although we can continue to simplify this expression, it is often acceptable to leave the derivative in this form, 
      especially if the problem does not explicitly ask for further simplification.
    </p> 
  </solution>
</example>


<example xml:id="ex-tangent-line-parameters">
  <statement>
    <p> Is there a point on the curve <m>y=ax^2</m> where the tangent line has the equation <m>y=6x+1</m>. 
      If so, find the values of <m>a</m> and the point of tangency.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution> 
    <p>
      The slope of the line <m>y=6x+1</m> is <m>6</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The derivative of the curve <m>y=ax^2</m> is <m>y'=2ax</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the line to be tangent to the curve, their slopes must be equal at some point. So we set:
    </p>
    <me>
      2ax = 6 \quad \Rightarrow \quad a = \frac{3}{x}.
    </me>
    <p>
      The point of tangency must also be on both curves. So we know that:
    </p>
    <me>
     6x+1 =  y = ax^2 = \frac{3}{x} \cdot x^2 = 3x.
    </me>
    <p>
      Solving for <m>x</m> gives: 
    </p>
    <me>
      3x = 6x + 1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad -3x = 1 \quad \Rightarrow \quad x = -\frac{1}{3}.
    </me>
    <p>
      Substituting back into (either) curve equation we get:
    </p>
    <me>
      y = 6\left(-\frac{1}{3}\right) + 1 = -2 + 1 = -1.
    </me>
    <p>
      And substituting this value back into our  <m>a = \frac{3}{x}</m> equation gives:
    </p>
      
    <me>
      a = \frac{3}{-\frac{1}{3}} = -9.
    </me>
    <p>
      Thus, the value of <m>a</m> is <m>-9</m>, and the point of tangency is <m>\left(-\frac{1}{3}, -1\right)</m>. You can verify in Desmos
      that the line <m>y=6x+1</m> is indeed tangent to the curve <m>y=-9x^2</m> at the point <m>\left(-\frac{1}{3}, -1\right)</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>



    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-trig">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-trig"/> Trigonometric Derivatives</title>

      <example xml:id="ex-tangent-line-trig">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>f(x) = 4\sin(x)+1</m> at the point where <m>x=\pi/6</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find the equation of the tangent line, we first need to find the slope of the tangent line at <m>x=\pi/6</m>. 
            We compute the derivative of <m>f(x)</m>:
          </p> 
            <me>
              f'(x) = 4\cos(x).
            </me>
            <p>Now we substitute <m>x=\pi/6</m> into the expression for <m>f'(x)</m> to find the slope of the tangent line:</p>
            <me>
              f'\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) = 4\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) = 4 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = 2\sqrt{3}.
            </me>
            <p>Next, we need to find the coordinates of the point on the graph at <m>x=\pi/6</m>. We compute:</p>
            <me>
              f\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) = 4\sin\left(\frac{\pi}{6}\right) + 1 = 4 \cdot \frac{1}{2} + 1 = 2 + 1 = 3.
            </me>
            <p>Thus, the point of tangency is <m>\left(\frac{\pi}{6}, 3\right)</m>. Using the point-slope form of a line, we can write the equation of the tangent line as:</p>
            <me>
              y - 3 = 2\sqrt{3}\left(x - \frac{\pi}{6}\right).
            </me>
              <p>
                Simplifying this gives:
          </p>
          <me>
            y = 2\sqrt{3}x - \frac{\pi\sqrt{3}}{3} + 3.
          </me>
        </solution>
      </example>

      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-trig-cycle">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f(x) = \sin(x)-\cos(x)</m>, find <m>f^{(21)}(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We first compute the first few derivatives of <m>f(x) = \sin(x)-\cos(x)</m>:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            f(x) &amp; = &amp; \sin(x)-\cos(x) \\
            f'(x) &amp; = &amp; \cos(x)+\sin(x) \\
            f''(x) &amp; = &amp; -\sin(x)+\cos(x) \\
            f'''(x) &amp; = &amp; -\cos(x)-\sin(x) \\
            f^{(4)}(x) &amp; = &amp; \sin(x)-\cos(x).
            \end{array}
          </me>
          <p>
            We see that <m>f^{(4)}(x) = f(x)</m>. This means that the derivatives of <m>f</m> repeat in a cycle of length 4. 
            To find <m>f^{(21)}(x)</m>, we can determine where 21 falls in this cycle by computing the remainder when 21 is divided by 4:
          </p>
          <me>
            21 \div 4 = 5 \text{ remainder } 1.
          </me>
          <p>
            Since the remainder is 1, we have:
          </p>
          <me>
            f^{(21)}(x) = f^{(1)}(x) = \cos(x)+\sin(x).
          </me> 
        </solution>
      </example>

      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-trig-product">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> if <m>y = \sqrt{x}\sin(x)\tan(x)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            We can apply the product rule multiple times to differentiate this function. 
            Let <m>u = \sqrt{x}</m>, <m>v = \sin(x)</m>, and <m>w = \tan(x)</m>. 
            Then we can write <m>y</m> as:
          </p>
          <me>
            y = uvw.
          </me>
          <p>
            To find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>, we can use the product rule in the following way:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            \dfrac{dy}{dx} &amp; = &amp; u'vw + uv'w + uvw' \\
            &amp; = &amp; \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}\sin(x)\tan(x) + \sqrt{x}\cos(x)\tan(x) + \sqrt{x}\sin(x)\sec^2(x).
            \end{array}
          </me>
        </solution>
      </example>


      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-trig-limit">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Evaluate the following limit: <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{\sin(x^2 - 4)}{x-2}</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using direct substitution, we find that the limit is of the form <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. We will 
            try to implement our <xref ref="thm-limit-sin-u-over-u"/> to evaluate this limit.
          </p>
          <p>
            Let <m>u = x^2 - 4</m>. Then as <m>x \to 2</m>, we have <m>u \to 0</m>. We can rewrite the limit by 
            multiplying and dividing by <m>x+2</m> to get the denominator to match what is inside of the sine function:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            \displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{\sin(x^2 - 4)}{x-2} &amp; = &amp; \displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{\sin(x^2-4)}{x-2} \cdot \frac{x+2}{x+2} \\
            &amp; = &amp; \displaystyle \lim_{x\to 2} \frac{\sin(x^2-4)}{x^2-4} \cdot (x+2) \\
            &amp; = &amp; \displaystyle \lim_{u\to 0} \frac{\sin(u)}{u} \cdot \lim_{x\to 2}(x+2) \\
            &amp; = &amp; 1 \cdot (2+2) = 4.
            \end{array}
          </me>
        </solution>
      </example>


    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-expChain">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-expChain"/> Exponential Functions and the Chain Rule</title>

      
      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-chain-exp"> 
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the function <m>f(x) = \left(x^2 + \sqrt{x}\right)^3</m>.
          </p>
          <p> (a) Find <m>f'(x)</m>.</p> 
          <p> (b) Find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p> (a) To find <m>f'(x)</m>, we can apply the chain rule. Let <m>u = x^2 + \sqrt{x}</m>, so that <m>f(x) = u^3</m>. 
          Then we have:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            f'(x) &amp; = &amp; 3u^2 \cdot u' \\
            &amp; = &amp; 3(x^2 + \sqrt{x})^2 \cdot (2x + \frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}).
            \end{array}
          </me>
          <p> (b) To find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of <m>f</m> at the point where <m>x=1</m>,
          we first need to find the coordinates of the point on the graph at <m>x=1</m>. We compute:
          </p>
          <me>
            f(1) = (1^2 + \sqrt{1})^3 = (1 + 1)^3 = 2^3 = 8.
          </me>
          <p>Thus, the point of tangency is <m>(1, 8)</m>. Next, we need to find the slope of the tangent line at <m>x=1</m>.
          We compute:
          </p>
          <me>
            f'(1) = 3(1^2 + \sqrt{1})^2 \cdot (2(1) + \frac{1}{2\sqrt{1}}) = 3(4) \cdot \frac{5}{2} = 30.
          </me>
          <p>Using the point-slope form of a line, we can write the equation of the tangent line as:</p>
          <me>
            y - 8 = 30(x - 1).
          </me>
          <p>Simplifying this gives:</p>
          <me>
            y = 30x - 22.
          </me>
          </solution>



        </example>


        <example xml:id="ex-derivative-trig-chain">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Find the derivative of the function <m>A(x) = \sin\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right) \sec(x^2)</m>.
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              The outermost operation is multiplication. Therfore we should begin by applying the product rule to differentiate this function. 
              Let <m>u = \sin\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right)</m> and <m>v = \sec(x^2)</m>. 
              Then we have:
            </p>
            <me>
              \begin{array}{rcl}
                u' &amp; = &amp; \cos\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right) \cdot \left(-\frac{1}{x^2}\right),\\
                v' &amp; = &amp; \sec(x^2)\tan(x^2) \cdot 2x \\
              \end{array}
            </me>
              <p>
                Now we can apply the product rule:
              </p>
            <me>
              \begin{array}{rcl}
               A'(x) &amp; = &amp; u'v + uv' \\
               &amp; = &amp; \cos\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right) \cdot \left(-\frac{1}{x^2}\right) \cdot \sec(x^2) + \sin\left(\dfrac{1}{x}\right) \cdot \sec(x^2)\tan(x^2) \cdot 2x.
              \end{array}
            </me>
          </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Consider the functions shown in the graph below.
            </p>

        <image width = "60%">
  <shortdescription>
    A coordinate grid from x = 0 to x = 5 and y = 0 to y = 5 showing two functions labeled f(x) and g(x).
The graph of g(x) is a downward opening parabola that passes through approximately (0, 0), reaches a maximum at (2, 4), 
and then decreases to (4, 0).
The graph of f(x) is piecewise linear. It decreases along a straight line from about (0, 2) to (3, 1), 
then increases along a straight line from (3, 1) to (5, 3).
  </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}
	\draw[->, thick] (-.3,0) -- (5.3,0);
	\draw[->, thick] (0,-.3) -- (0,5.3);
	\draw[thin] (0,0) grid (5,5);
	\begin{scope}
		\clip (-.3,0) rectangle (5.3,5.3); 
		\draw[very thick] plot[domain=0:5, smooth] (\x, {4-(2-\x)^2});
		\draw[very thick] (0,2)-- (3,1) -- (5,3);
			
		
	\end{scope}
	\draw (4.5,3.3) node {$f(x)$};
	\draw (4.5,.3) node {$g(x)$};
	\foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5} {
		\draw (\x, 2pt) -- (\x, -2pt) node[font=\small, below] {\x};
		\draw (2pt, \x) -- ( -2pt, \x) node[font=\small, left] {\x};
		
	} 
\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>

      <p> If <m>A(x) = g(f(x))</m>, find <m>A'(4)</m>.</p>

          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              To find <m>A'(4)</m>, we can apply the chain rule. The chain rule states that if <m>A(x) = g(f(x))</m>, then
              <me>
                A'(x) = g'(f(x)) \cdot f'(x).
              </me>
              Therefore, we need to find <m>g'(f(4))</m> and <m>f'(4)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              From the graph, we can see that <m>f(4) = 2</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              To find <m>f'(4)</m>, we need to find the slope of the graph of <m>f</m> at <m>x=4</m>. 
              The graph of <m>f</m> is piecewise linear, and at <m>x=4</m>, it is on the increasing linear segment from (3,1) to (5,3). 
              The slope is <m>\frac{3-1}{5-3} = 1</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              To find <m>g'(f(4)) = g'(2)</m>, we need to find the slope of the graph of <m>g</m> at <m>x=2</m>. 
              From the graph, we can see that the graph of <m>g</m> is horizontal at <m>x=2</m> so therefore the slope is <m>0</m>.
            </p>
            <me>
              A'(4) = g'(f(4)) \cdot f'(4) = 0 \cdot 1 = 0.
            </me>
          </solution>
        </example>


        <example xml:id="ex-derivative-chain-interpret">
            <statement>
    <p>
      A metal rod has a constant circular cross-sectional area 
      <m>A = 20</m> square centimeters.
      Its volume (in cubic centimeters) is a function of its length <m>L</m> (in centimeters):
    </p>

    <me>
      V(L) = AL.
    </me>

    <p>
      Due to heating, the rod’s length depends on temperature <m>T</m> 
      (in degrees Celsius) by
    </p>

    <me>
      L(T) = 50\bigl(1 + 0.001T\bigr).
    </me>

    <p>
      (a) Compute <m>\dfrac{dV}{dL}</m>. What are the units of 
      <m>\dfrac{dV}{dL}</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Compute <m>\dfrac{dL}{dT}</m> and evaluate it at 
      <m>T = 100</m>. What are the units of 
      <m>\dfrac{dL}{dT}</m>?
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) Use the Chain Rule to compute <m>\dfrac{dV}{dT}</m> at 
      <m>T = 100^\circ\text{C}</m>. Interpret the meaning of this value in the context of the problem, including its units.
    </p>

  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) To compute <m>\dfrac{dV}{dL}</m>, we differentiate <m>V(L) = AL</m> with respect to <m>L</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{dV}{dL} = A = 20.
    </me>
    <p>
      The units of <m>\dfrac{dV}{dL}</m> are cubic centimeters per centimeter (cm<m>^3</m>/cm).
    </p>
    <p>
      (b) To compute <m>\dfrac{dL}{dT}</m>, we differentiate <m>L(T) = 50\bigl(1 + 0.001T\bigr)</m> with respect to <m>T</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{dL}{dT} = 50 \cdot 0.001 = 0.05.
    </me>
    <p>
      Evaluating at <m>T = 100</m> gives:
    </p>
    <me>
      \left.\frac{dL}{dT}\right|_{T=100} = 0.05.
    </me>
    <p>
      The units of <m>\dfrac{dL}{dT}</m> are centimeters per degree Celsius (<m>\text{cm}/^\circ\text{C}</m>).
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) To compute <m>\dfrac{dV}{dT}</m> at <m>T = 100</m>, we can use the Chain Rule:
    </p>
    <me>
      \left.\frac{dV}{dT}\right|_{T=100} = \left.\frac{dV}{dL}\right|_{L=L(100)} \cdot \left.\frac{dL}{dT}\right|_{T=100}.
    </me>
    <p>
      We already know that <m>\dfrac{dV}{dL} = 20</m> and <m>\dfrac{dL}{dT}\big|_{T=100} = 0.05</m>. 
    Therefore, we can compute <m>\dfrac{dV}{dT}\big|_{T=100}</m> as follows:
    </p>
    <me>
      \left.\frac{dV}{dT}\right|_{T=100} = 20 \cdot 0.05 = 1.
    </me>
    <p>
      The units of <m>\dfrac{dV}{dT}</m> are cubic centimeters per degree Celsius (<m>\text{cm}^3/^\circ\text{C}</m>). 
      This value means that at a temperature of 100 degrees Celsius, 
      the volume of the rod is increasing at a rate of 1 cubic centimeter per degree Celsius.
    </p> 
  </solution>
        </example>


    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-implicit">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-implicit"/> Implicit Differentiation</title>


      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-implicit-exp"> 
   <statement>
    <p>
      Find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> if
    </p>
    <me>
      e^{2x - y} = \cos(3y).
    </me>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      To find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>, we differentiate both sides of the equation with respect to <m>x</m>, treating <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>. 
      We apply the chain rule as needed:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \frac{d}{dx}\!\left(e^{2x - y}\right) &amp; = &amp; \frac{d}{dx}\!\left(\cos(3y)\right) \\
      e^{2x - y} \cdot (2 - y') &amp; = &amp; -\sin(3y) \cdot 3y' \\
      2e^{2x - y} - e^{2x - y}y' &amp; = &amp; -3\sin(3y)y' \\
      3\sin(3y)y' - e^{2x - y}y' &amp; = &amp; -2e^{2x - y} \\
      y'(3\sin(3y) - e^{2x - y}) &amp; = &amp; -2e^{2x - y} \\
      y' &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{-2e^{2x - y}}{3\sin(3y) - e^{2x - y}}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
  </solution>

      </example>


      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-implicit-curve-horizontal-vertical">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the curve defined implicitly by
      <m>x^2y + y^3 = 4x</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) Find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> (as a function of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>).
    </p>

    <p>
      (b) Find the points on the curve where the tangent line is horizontal.
    </p>

    <p>
      (c) Find the points on the curve where the tangent line is vertical.
    </p>

  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) To find <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>, we differentiate both sides of the equation <m>x^2y + y^3 = 4x</m> with respect to <m>x</m>, 
      treating <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>. 
      We apply the product rule and chain rule as needed:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      (2x)y + x^2y' + 3y^2y' &amp; =  &amp; 4\\
      x^2y' + 3y^2y' &amp; = &amp; 4 - 2xy \\
      y'(x^2 + 3y^2) &amp; = &amp; 4 - 2xy \\
      y' &amp; = &amp; \dfrac{4 - 2xy}{x^2 + 3y^2}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      (b) The tangent line is horizontal where <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx} = 0</m>. 
      This occurs when the numerator of the expression for <m>y'</m> is zero: 
    </p>
    <me>
      4 - 2xy = 0 \quad \Rightarrow \quad 2xy = 4 \quad \Rightarrow \quad xy = 2.
    </me>
    <p>
      We can substitute <m>y = \frac{2}{x}</m> into the original equation to find the corresponding <m>x</m> values:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      x^2\left(\frac{2}{x}\right) + \left(\frac{2}{x}\right)^3 &amp; = &amp; 4x \\
      2x + \frac{8}{x^3} &amp; = &amp; 4x \\
      \frac{8}{x^3} &amp; = &amp; 2x \\
      8 &amp; = &amp; 2x^4 \\
      x^4 &amp; = &amp; 4 \\
      x &amp; = &amp; \sqrt[4]{4} = \sqrt{2} \text{ or } x = -\sqrt{2}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      Substituting these values back into <m>y = \frac{2}{x}</m> gives the corresponding <m>y</m> values:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      y &amp; = &amp; \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} = \sqrt{2} \quad \text{when } x = \sqrt{2}, \\
      y &amp; = &amp; \frac{2}{-\sqrt{2}} = -\sqrt{2} \quad \text{when } x = -\sqrt{2}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      Thus, the points on the curve where the tangent line is horizontal are <m>\left(\sqrt{2}, \sqrt{2}\right)</m> and <m>\left(-\sqrt{2}, -\sqrt{2}\right)</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) When <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is undefined the tangent line can be vertical. 
      This occurs when the denominator of the expression for <m>y'</m> is zero:
      <m>x^2 + 3y^2 = 0</m>.
      Since <m>x^2 \geq 0</m> and <m>3y^2 \geq 0</m>, the only solution is <m>x = 0</m> and <m>y = 0</m>. 
      We can verify that <m>(0,0)</m> is on the curve since substituting into the original equation gives <m>0 + 0 = 0</m>.
      Note that at this point the numerator of the expression for <m>y'</m> is not zero, so the limit of <m>y'</m> as we approach <m>(0,0)</m> 
      does not exist and the tangent line is vertical at this point. 
      So therefore, the point on the curve where the tangent line is vertical is <m>(0,0)</m>.
    </p>

    </solution>

      </example>




    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-deriv-inverse">
      <title><xref ref="sec-derivative-inverse"/> Inverse Functions and Their Derivatives</title>

      
      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-inverse-trig">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f(x) = 2^{\sin^{-1}(x)}</m>. Find <m>f'(0)</m>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            To find <m>f'(0)</m>, we can apply the chain rule. Let <m>u = \sin^{-1}(x)</m>, so that <m>f(x) = 2^u</m>. 
            Then we have:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            f'(x) &amp; = &amp; 2^u \cdot \ln(2) \cdot u' \\
            &amp; = &amp; 2^{\sin^{-1}(x)} \cdot \ln(2) \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}.
            \end{array}
          </me>
          <p>
            Now we can substitute <m>x=0</m> into the expression for <m>f'(x)</m> to find <m>f'(0)</m>:
          </p>
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            f'(0) &amp; = &amp; 2^{\sin^{-1}(0)} \cdot \ln(2) \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-0^2}} \\
            &amp; = &amp; 2^0 \cdot \ln(2) \cdot 1 = \ln(2).
            \end{array}
          </me>
        </solution>
      </example>


      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-inverse-exp-constant">
         <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose 
      <m>f(x) = c e^{2x} + \ln(x^2 + 1)</m>
      for some constant <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      What value of <m>c</m> makes 
      <m>f'(0) = 3</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      To find the value of <m>c</m> that makes <m>f'(0) = 3</m>, we first need to compute <m>f'(x)</m>. 
      We differentiate <m>f(x) = c e^{2x} + \ln(x^2 + 1)</m> with respect to <m>x</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f'(x) &amp; = &amp; 2c e^{2x} + \frac{2x}{x^2 + 1}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      Now we can substitute <m>x=0</m> into the expression for <m>f'(x)</m> to find <m>f'(0)</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      f'(0) &amp; = &amp; 2c e^{0} + \frac{0}{0^2 + 1} \\
      &amp; = &amp; 2c.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      We want <m>f'(0) = 3</m>, so we set
    </p>
    <me>
      2c = 3 \quad \implies \quad c = \frac{3}{2}.
    </me>
  </solution>

      </example>



      <example xml:id="ex-derivative-inverse-findExplicit">
          <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the curve given by the equation
      <m>x^{1/3} + y^{1/3} = 4</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      (a) Find the derivative <m>y'</m>.
    </p>
       <p>
      (b) Use your answer from (a) and the equation of the curve to find <m>y'(x)</m>.
      That is, write <m>y'</m> as a function of <m>x</m> only.
    </p>
    <p>
      (c) Evaluate <m>y'(1)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      (a) To find the derivative <m>y'</m>, we differentiate both sides of the equation <m>x^{1/3} + y^{1/3} = 4</m> with respect to <m>x</m>, 
      treating <m>y</m> as a function of <m>x</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \frac{d}{dx}\left(x^{1/3} + y^{1/3}\right) &amp; = &amp; \frac{d}{dx}(4) \\
      \frac{1}{3}x^{-2/3} + \frac{1}{3}y^{-2/3} \cdot y' &amp; = &amp; 0 \\
      y' &amp; = &amp; -\dfrac{x^{-2/3}}{y^{-2/3}} = -\dfrac{y^{2/3}}{x^{2/3}}.
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p>
      (b) Using the equation of the curve, we can express <m>y</m> in terms of <m>x</m>. 
      From <m>x^{1/3} + y^{1/3} = 4</m>, we have <m>y^{1/3} = 4 - x^{1/3}</m>, so <m>y^{2/3} = (4 - x^{1/3})^2</m>.
      Substituting this into the expression for <m>y'</m> from part (a):
    </p>
    <me>
      y'(x) = -\dfrac{(4 - x^{1/3})^2}{x^{2/3}} 
    </me>
    <p>
      (c) To evaluate <m>y'(1)</m>, we substitute <m>x=1</m> into the expression for <m>y'(x)</m>:
    </p>
    <me>
      y'(1) = -\dfrac{(4 - 1^{1/3})^2}{1^{2/3}} = -(4 - 1)^2 = -9.
    </me>
  </solution>
    
      </example>


    </subsection>

</section>